    <h2>FAQ</h2>
    <h3>Is Cursor better than Windsurf for AI coding?</h3>
    <p>Cursor has a more mature ecosystem and faster autocomplete. Windsurf offers unique Cascade AI flows and a cleaner approach to multi-file editing. Cursor is better for developers who want the most polished, feature-rich AI IDE. Windsurf is excellent for developers who want a streamlined AI experience with strong open-source foundations.</p>
    <h3>Is Windsurf completely free?</h3>
    <p>Windsurf offers a generous free tier with unlimited basic autocomplete and limited AI chat/composer requests. The Pro tier at $15 per month unlocks higher limits and advanced features. This makes Windsurf one of the more affordable AI IDE options available.</p>
    <h3>Which AI IDE has better code generation?</h3>
    <p>Both Cursor and Windsurf produce high-quality code generation. Cursor's Composer and Windsurf's Cascade handle multi-file generation well. Cursor slightly edges ahead on accuracy for complex patterns due to its more mature model tuning and larger user feedback loop. Windsurf excels at generating clean, idiomatic code that follows modern best practices.</p>
    <h3>Can I use Windsurf extensions in VS Code?</h3>
    <p>Windsurf is built on VS Code (via the open-source Continue project foundation) and maintains good compatibility with the VS Code extension marketplace. Most popular VS Code extensions work in Windsurf, though some edge cases may have minor compatibility differences compared to vanilla VS Code or Cursor.</p>
    <h3>Should I switch from Cursor to Windsurf?</h3>
    <p>If you are happy with Cursor, there is no urgent need to switch. Windsurf is worth trying if you want Cascade's unique flow-based AI interaction, prefer a lighter-weight IDE, or want to save money on the Pro tier ($15 vs $20). Many developers use both for different project types.</p>
